title.narrative: Productive Safety Net Program/ Development Food Assistance Program- CRS

description.narrative: (Ethiopia): The Title II-funded Development Food Assistance Program (DFAP) is managed by Catholic Relief Services (CRS-Ethiopia) with a goal of protecting household assets, sustaining food consumption levels, and creating communal assets, in order to reduce food insecurity as well as increase resilience to climate change by integrating effective adaptive strategies. The mechanism also supports an urban safety net through the Missionaries of Charity (MOC), which reaches the destitute including orphans, through 15 auspices.With FY 2015 funds, CRS will provide food to more than 220,000 beneficiaries, of which 172,908 beneficiaries will engage in public works while others will receive food without conditionality. Support provided through the MOC will reach 11,350 beneficiaries. In addition, CRS implements integrated watershed management, water points development, and social and economic infrastructure development, as well as nutrition, sanitation and hygiene activities.Natural resource management activities will include watershed rehabilitation, reforestation, area closures, groundwater recharge, and soil fertility improvement; protection against erosion, flooding and landslides; and increases to vegetation cover. Smallholder production activities will focus on small-scale irrigation for high value crops, such as fruits and vegetables. CRS will continue to promote technologies and management practices which increase efficient use of water resources. These activities will promote sustainable economic opportunities that are suited to the physical environment while addressing the impact of climate change and increase beneficiaries' resilience to shocks.
